We also have a 44 bed unit. We support

00:01:06.800 --> 00:01:09.560
most of the clients that live in that space.

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:14.040
Previously to that they were either precariously housed or

00:01:15.060 --> 00:01:27.760
homeless, visibly homeless in the community. Stigma care is one thing that's

00:01:27.760 --> 00:01:32.340
on the forefront of all my colleagues that work for the intensive case

00:01:32.340 --> 00:01:38.240
management team. Through that we try to use a client centered approach,

00:01:38.440 --> 00:01:46.100
a trauma informed approach and to best support our clients and advocate

00:01:46.100 --> 00:01:50.920
on their behalf. It is something that unfortunately

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:55.900
we do see a lot of in hospital and in community and

00:01:56.660 --> 00:02:00.300
we try to be the advocates for these people who sometimes don't have

00:02:00.380 --> 00:02:06.600
a voice in these situations. It's not an easy fix. It's not like

00:02:06.600 --> 00:02:09.620
setting an arm and doing an x ray and putting a cast on

00:02:09.630 --> 00:02:12.620
and you're good in six weeks. This is just, every day is ever

00:02:12.620 --> 00:02:17.160
changing and there is no perfect outcome. So I think that can also

00:02:17.160 --> 00:02:21.360
be overwhelming for people and they get anxious and they just don't know

00:02:21.360 --> 00:02:24.640
how to deal with seeing someone in that situation again and again and

00:02:24.640 --> 00:02:39.240
again and again and again. So stigma can happen

00:02:39.820 --> 00:02:44.900
and does happen unfortunately in many different situations and paths I cross

00:02:44.900 --> 00:02:47.900
in my line of work which could range from the community to the

